title: Yes, please
on-arrival: progress = 7
tags: start_frmwrk

Me: Yes, please.

Facilyn: Great.

Facilyn slides a pen and a sheet of thin paper onto the table.

Facilyn: When we try to “fix” something, we usually jump straight to the problem.

Facilyn: Let’s not do that.

She draws a slow circle on the paper.

Facilyn: Let’s start with something simpler.

She writes three words in the circle, leaving room between them:

Paper: People 

Paper: Resources 

Paper: Money

Facilyn: A manageable whole has three essentials: <br> • the people who make decisions <br> • the resources within reach <br> • and the money you have — or can generate

Facilyn: So before we talk about changing anything...

She nudges the pen a little closer to you.

Facilyn: We define the whole you’re actually managing.

- #whole_u_mgmt

@wum_explanation
title: Why do we define the "whole"?
max-visits: 1
order: 10
tags: whole_u_mgmt

Me: Why do we define the "whole"?

Facilyn: We’re trained to think in parts. Departments. Issues. Boxes you can label.

Facilyn: But living systems don’t function that way.

She glances toward the steaming tea.

Facilyn: Hydrogen isn’t water. Oxygen isn’t water.

Facilyn: You can study them for weeks and still miss what water *is*.

Facilyn: When you define your whole, you start to see two things: what really influences it — and how your choices ripple outward.

Her finger moves outward beyond the circle.

Facilyn: Most management fails because we never define the whole. We manage fragments and hope they behave.

She taps the page lightly.

Facilyn: This is where we stop hoping.

- #whole_u_mgmt
